üîòThere is no specific treatment approved for monkeypox, but most people get better on their own without treatment. 

üîòIf you experience symptoms, talk to your doctor. If you do not have one, call 311 and a provider will check your symptoms and may order testing.

üîòEligible New Yorkers 18 and older who may have been recently exposed to monkeypox can get a recently FDA approved vaccine.

üîòGetting vaccinated after a recent exposure reduces the chance of you getting monkeypox, and it can reduce symptoms if you do get it.

üîò#Monkeypox is most often spread through direct contact with a rash or sores of someone who has the virus.

üîòIt can also be spread through contact with clothing, bedding, etc. used by an infected person, or from respiratory droplets passed through prolonged face-to-face contact

üîò#Monkeypox symptoms, which appear 1-3 weeks after exposure, include: An itchy rash/skin sores, fever, headache, tiredness and swollen lymph nodes.
